results.notes:
In damp sphagnum.
Four fruit bodies seen in the thumbnail were found within a singly square foot; the fourth (largest) fruit body was 2-3 feet away.
Caps with broad umbo, some hairs across the cap surface (which seems to suggest G. paludosa). Margins vaguely grooved.
Spores 9-11 × 6.5-7, appearing smooth at 400x, dextrinoid (which points away from G. paludosa).
Spores from similar collections recently made in sphagnum swamps have reacted variably to the application if Melzers, virtually no darkening to purplish-brown (which I interpret as dextrinoid). These spores seem to qualify as dextrinoid.
By the time I got around to trying to scope this material the fruit bodies had partially dried. In this condition I found the material very difficult to work with.

results.notes:
Eight collections seen here, in each case coming from one of eight different 1 square yard areas.
Caps umbonate, variably striate, lacking copious fibrils but occasionally showing a few patchy whitish areas. Largest central arcs measuring from around 10 mm to around 30 mm.
Stipes with patchy whitish velar remains, occasionally forming a thin rung oir ring zone near the apex.
Spores variably dextrinoid (weakly to moderate), 8-11(12) x 5.5-7(7.5) (most 8-10 × 5.5-6.6), not calyptrate.
Hymenial cystidia (probably all cheilocystidia as in each case they were found only along one border of a gill smash mount), thin-walled, variably shaped but many seen as a protruding cylindrical or variably thick neck with or without slightly enlarged rounded apex; a few seen with inflated posterior (or possibly the midsection if the posterior was not seen).
The two prime suspects here (relatively large fruit bodies with velar patches on the stipes and non-calyptrate spores 8-11 × 5.5-7) seem to be G. plaludosa and G. sphagnorum. These collections better match the latter, based upon dextrinoid spores and caps lacking significant fibers.
